2. IEC 62443: Overview and Key Principles

2.1 The Standard Series

IEC 62443 is a multi-part standard covering the entire lifecycle of industrial automation and control systems:

Part Title Focus
1-1 Terminology, Concepts and Models Foundational definitions
1-3 System Security Compliance Metrics Security levels, SL 1–4
2-1 IACS Security Management System Policies, procedures, governance
2-3 Patch Management Vulnerability management
3-2 Security Risk Assessment Risk identification and mitigation
3-3 System Security Requirements Technical controls
4-1 Product Security Development Secure development lifecycle
4-2 Technical Security Requirements Component-level security

2.2 Core Concepts

Concept Definition
Zones Logical grouping of assets with common security requirements
Conduits Communication channels between zones
Security Level (SL) Target maturity of cybersecurity capability (SL 1–4)
SL-T (Target) Desired SL for a zone/conduit
SL-C (Capability) SL the system can achieve
SL-A (Achieved) Actual SL after deployment

2.3 The 7 Foundational Requirements

IEC 62443-3-3 defines seven foundational requirements (FRs) for system security:

FR Requirement Description
FR 1 Identification and Authentication Control IAC — Who is accessing?
FR 2 Use Control UC — What can they do?
FR 3 System Integrity SI — Has the system been tampered with?
FR 4 Data Confidentiality DC — Is data protected?
FR 5 Restricted Data Flow RDF — Is network traffic controlled?
FR 6 Timely Response to Events TRE — Is there rapid detection and response?
FR 7 Resource Availability RA — Can the system be overwhelmed?

