4. Mapping ST-T1024 to IEC 62443 Foundational Requirements

FR 1: Identification and Authentication Control

Requirement ST-T1024 Implementation
Access control SK-1024 protocol ensures only authorized updates. No remote access.
Authentication Cryptographic signatures on SRAM updates. Hardware-enforced.
Account management Single sovereign authority — no multiple accounts to manage.

ST-T1024 Position: Exceeds requirements — physical authentication (SK-1024) beats software authentication.

---

FR 2: Use Control

Requirement ST-T1024 Implementation
Least privilege Each tile knows only its domain. No tile has full system access.
Separation of duties Tiles are independent. No cross-tile communication.
Session control Each query is a discrete session. No persistent state.

ST-T1024 Position: Strong alignment — tiling enforces least privilege by hardware design.

---

FR 3: System Integrity

Requirement ST-T1024 Implementation
Tamper detection 75% ROM immutable — cannot be tampered with.
Tamper prevention SRAM encrypted — cannot be modified without SK-1024 key.
Event logging FSM state transitions are observable and traceable.
Integrity verification Deterministic output — any change is detectable.

ST-T1024 Position: Excellence — hardware-enforced integrity is superior to software-only solutions.

---

FR 4: Data Confidentiality

Requirement ST-T1024 Implementation
Encryption SRAM data encrypted. ROM is public — no secrets there.
Data isolation Tiles isolate data by domain. No cross-tile leakage.
Secure storage ROM is immutable. SRAM is encrypted.

ST-T1024 Position: Strong — air-gapped execution means data never leaves the device.

